Visualizing the tree with the rattle library

fancyRpartPlot(rpartTree)

temp <- rpart.control(xval=10, minbucket = 2,minsplit = 4,cp = 0)
dfit <- rpart(Glass_Type~ . , data = train, control=temp)
fancyRpartPlot(dfit)

Finding the best complexity parameter

10- fold cross validation

fitControl <- trainControl(method = 'cv', number=10)

Grid <- expand.grid(cp=seq(0, 0.05, 0.005))

# Running the training 

trained_tree <- train(Glass_Type ~ . , data = train, method = 'rpart',
trControl=fitControl, metric = "", maximize=TRUE, tuneGrid=Grid)
## Warning in train.default(x, y, weights = w, ...): The metric "" was not in the
## result set. Accuracy will be used instead.

Bagging Tree

library(ipred)


gbag <- bagging(Glass_Type ~ ., data = glass1, nbagg = 10, coob=TRUE)
print(gbag)
## 
## Bagging classification trees with 10 bootstrap replications 
## 
## Call: bagging.data.frame(formula = Glass_Type ~ ., data = glass1, nbagg = 10, 
##     coob = TRUE)
## 
## Out-of-bag estimate of misclassification error:  0.3099
gbag2 <- bagging(Glass_Type ~ ., data = glass1, nbagg = 70 , coob=TRUE)
print(gbag2)
## 
## Bagging classification trees with 70 bootstrap replications 
## 
## Call: bagging.data.frame(formula = Glass_Type ~ ., data = glass1, nbagg = 70, 
##     coob = TRUE)
## 
## Out-of-bag estimate of misclassification error:  0.23
gbag3 <- bagging(Glass_Type ~ ., data = glass1, nbagg =35 , coob=TRUE)
print(gbag3)
## 
## Bagging classification trees with 35 bootstrap replications 
## 
## Call: bagging.data.frame(formula = Glass_Type ~ ., data = glass1, nbagg = 35, 
##     coob = TRUE)
## 
## Out-of-bag estimate of misclassification error:  0.2347
# It seems having nbagg < 10 returned an error not allowing the computaion # of O.O.B for a "small number of bags".  The optimal range seemed to be near 70.
